Step 1: Create the Lambda Function
Go to the AWS Lambda Console.

Click Create function.

Choose Author from scratch.

Function name: AttendanceCalculator.

Runtime: Select Python 3.12 (or the latest 3.x).

Permissions: Click "Change default execution role" and select Use an existing role. Pick the role you just added the policy to.

Click Create function.






1. The "Local" Way (For Testing Only)
You can keep the index.html file right on your laptop's desktop.

How it works: You just double-click the file, and it opens in Chrome.

The Catch: Only you can see it. If you send the link C:/Users/Saksham/index.html to a friend at GGSIPU, it won't work for them because that file is only on your hard drive.

2. The "Cloud" Way (AWS Amplify - Recommended)
This is the professional way to do it. You "host" the file on AWS so it gets a public URL like https://main.d12345.amplifyapp.com.

Why use AWS Amplify?

Global Access: Your classmates can check their 70% attendance from their own phones while sitting in the canteen.

SSL Security: It automatically gives you https://, which makes the site look official.


How to put your file on AWS Amplify:
Prepare your file: Make sure your index.html has the CSS inside the <style> tags (like the code I gave you earlier) and that you have pasted your API Gateway URL into the JavaScript section.

Go to AWS Console: Search for AWS Amplify.

Deploy without Git:

Click "Create new app".

Select "Deploy without Git provider".

Give it a name: GGSIPU-Attendance-Portal.

Drag and Drop: Simply drag your index.html file into the box.

Save and Deploy: Within 30 seconds, AWS will give you a "Domain" link. Click it, and your dashboard is live!
